Parliament did not support an amendment to release Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the doors to the release of the ex-Minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes at the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the alleged signing of a disadvantaged agreement with Russia for Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not yet final, the appellate court has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West there have been doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code condemning the former Prime Minister was supported by 147 Members in the vote.
For its approval, 226 votes were required.
