History of IBM: from the cheese cutter to space flights
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, being its original name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was already adopted in 1924 - it was originally a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The basis that led to the birth of IBM emerges from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous "squeeze clock", which allows controlling the entry and exit of the employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also presided over his supervisory council.
Flint posted the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the company's management.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM ( Watson's ideas remain the firm basis on which corporate culture and identity are supported).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, started with the production and sale of all types of business equipment, from meat and cheese cutters to register boxes.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, the billing doubled by $9 million and began the great expansion of the company on the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after almost forty years occupying the chief's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "pecese", which established the standard of computers of that time, came to the market under the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consultancy part of Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer full advice and services of high value added.
