How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 in Czechoslovakia there were only five authorized state travel agencies: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases travel only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
The Czech tourists therefore went on vacation to the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime bowed west and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies offered in those times also travel to the West, but one should put on the tail with a sleeping bag and spend like this all night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", which could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a currency guarantee, it was not possible to obtain resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs would acquire.
The way in which the Czechs traveled has been undergoing a genuine revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend holidays in the RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that Croatia was not able to travel freely until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa exemptions were imposed to travel to the neighbouring states of Western Europe, causing a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, were not fed up with excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris the Czech groups were sleeping in the parks in tents, as our income from then did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs at that time was to take food with them (conserves, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it also the average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in demand for travel agencies began, from 1997 onwards regularly, to prepare travel using charter flights connections, making travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
In the late 1990s, the Czechs were already traveling without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the United States, which further simplified our trips.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism occurred already in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists leave for far and hot countries. This winter will fly directly from Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit them about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their foreign holidays (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 Czech krona per head on trips abroad, including expenses on the stay site.
