The walls have eyes: How researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the extreme right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy who aerated his anti-immigrant views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having committed a massacre in Norway in July, who left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time before his attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - you just have to enter Facebook.
"We realized that it was not so difficult to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the main author of a recent report on European digital populism by the DEMOS British study center.
Facebook's personal information range is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy - the way sellers have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans from right-wing groups across Europe and then directed them ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
Upon reaching through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers from 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a completely new way to do an investigation," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not quite surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry with immigration.
However, in a kind of turn, "those who combine their activism online with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
DEMOS' work is just an example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in the "I like", messages on the walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating an increase in research, boosting the number of academic works with the name of the site in the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't get close to with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You would have to go through the party, and they would never allow you access," says Bartlett.
"Facebook eliminates all that - you go to them directly."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that university students who talked about their drunken feats on Facebook had a significantly greater risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that students' colleagues, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student publish too many state updates with their drunks.
"You can't deal with a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, the co-author of Moreno and director of the Children's Health, Behaviour and Development Centre at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk that otherwise would not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "pinching" its own population to obtain data.
The site's Data Team has developed statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and an index of National Happiness (mainly using the information that you can access - defenders of digital freedom long ago who argue that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice to be able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know?
While researchers have well defined guidelines on how to collect your data offline, online is a free bar for all.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining his profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study he conducted with the Facebook public walls of students.
"As for them, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that an investigation theme is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know that part of a user's profile information and wall messages are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn says.
