This slightly re-edited archive material is the base of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview that arrives at the Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose their technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
In four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for precision.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism goes out to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster towards the topics or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or the iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The lost interview, when Jobs evaluates what other companies see doing right and wrong, and offers their own vision of the future of computers.
One thing is to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs' career, but there is something raw and inspiring in Jobs that we see here, the anxious dreamer at the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and must be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned how to run a business:
