Legends about traps in school and university exams are very widespread.
There have been cases in which teachers have given the responses of the exams to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deceit do we find?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Identifying lies, or "locating lies", is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades in prestigious universities that carried out research projects in depth, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lies have been contested.
The liars do look in the eyes.
They don't always tartamude, balbuce, rubore, or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfaced expressions, the formation of questions and times.
I spent several years studying scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps to navigate through our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include recruitment, interviews, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel comfortable, handling their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know by the investigations that the extroverts lie more than the introverts, that men say more "faith-oriented lies to themselves," while women lie more "focused on others" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their couples than people who are not married (but the lies they usually say tend to be "great").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty by lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual conduct.
This is called "creating a baseline".
It helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Watch the subject's position, laughter and vocal feature.
You better know if someone usually hits his foot all the time so he doesn't make unfair accusations when he sees his feet hitting in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for misleading, verbal and non-verbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper part of the body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean towards an exit, change their position significantly or exhibit a "post-interviewed shock" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of position once all the difficult questions have ended.
Often interrogators make falsely see that the interview has ended only to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used the past time as he claimed that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a distance language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question, "Well... to tell the truth... to what I know... to my understanding."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
