The diatribe of the singer of "Lady Marmalade" scared Genevieve Monk, 18 months old, so much that she suffered "changes of personality, sleep disorders" and "increased her fear of strangers," says her family at the Manhattan Supreme Court.
It was November 10 last year when stageist Kevin Monk, his wife, Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were preparing to go on a family trip.
While Kevin Monk took the car, Roseanna Monk came down to the lobby of the Riverside Boulevard building, with his luggage, taking Genevieve.
Roseanna Monk said he stood near the door and put his daughter on the ground for a moment.
"Someone came over the back and said to me, "Do you know what your daughter is doing?' I said "yes and I went to get her," he said.
LaBelle warned the pregnant woman angry.
"He said in an aggressive tone, "I shouldn't have left his daughter near the door," said Roseanna Monk.
"I said, "I have no interest in what you say or think."
He got angry and started using bad words - the word C and the word J out loud...
He had a bottle of water and started throwing the water out of the bottle on me."
He said Genevieve got hysterical.
"I told this woman, "Look what you've done to my daughter," said the girl's mother.
"LaBelle staggered over the mother -- who was still subject to Genevieve -- and had to be contained by her environment and withdrawn to a car waiting for her," Roseanna Monk said.
The little girl was crying so loud that she threw up, she added.
Later, the family sent a note asking for an apology from LaBelle, but did not get an answer.
The lawyer and LaBelle's representatives did not return the calls to comment on what happened.
The lawsuit seeks unspecified damage, but the family lawyer, Sam Davis, said that he took the case for free and that the family plans to donate all the money that he can get to a child support association with cancer.
"The purpose is to make Patti LaBelle responsible for his behavior," Davis said.
"That kind of behavior is completely unacceptable, especially when it goes to a kindergarten teacher who takes an 18-month-old in arms."
Climate Adversity Stopped the Economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's management, Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, lowered foreign investment and contracted the economy
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, this is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, self-denominated for change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, but there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing millions of losses to the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3,6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic fall of 31,16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of impacts on the frosts, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage in 582 thousand 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main sinister crops were vegetables, maize and garbanzo.
The fall in economic activity has led, until November, to a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was observed as from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Economically Active Population, for the second quarter the rate rose to 5.28 per cent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate that in the number of people throws more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
"What is being seen is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including loss of liquidity on the market because of the effects of a resource restriction by the legislation adopted at the congress to combat money laundering, since for people who take dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something," he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes noted that there is also a demographic factor in the increase in unemployment.
"The number of people leaving the state looking for work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties to get in, and secondly because entering they already have a lot of difficulties to find work, these people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which makes unemployment rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that prevails among the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population in the state works without being quoted as a worker to any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the state's labour loss is low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Insurance Institute and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there was the greatest decrease in direct foreign investment over the past 10 years, according to the State FDI's Ministry of Economy from January to June amounted to $630,000, 697, representing a decrease of 87.74 per cent compared to the $5 million, 143 thousand, 312 recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government accounts for a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
Faced with the scenario of economic contraction, the state government in July requested the state congress to approve a credit for 3 billion pesos, which would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the local congress was 2 billion 600 million pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, Mario López Valdés' first year of government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 he lacked the harmonization of the wills of the various sectors, including the government of the state itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensively to regain the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, we failed to align the effort of all and above all the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economicitude
Loredo Lopez stated that events like the freezings of early year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows for an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing far below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he stated that it is necessary to prosecute the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the state's vocation and economic direction, because it is important that Sinaloa devote all the potential of the material and human resource it has," he said.
Work to do
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has been striving to achieve good results in various areas, in the area of economic development there are some progress but it is important that a long-term programme be developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its conduct of public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the government is being more inclusive, what I can say is that there is work done and I think the government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
