Court validated "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
Replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional disputes brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogic blackout" from 2021 to 2015, not meeting the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to concrete the transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and the decree remains in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and of reservation of law.
In favour of the project only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree, and in admitting the demands, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and of all actions in it arranged for digital transition.
The Ministers' Plenary also decided to dismiss the appeal filed by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also by Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his statement, the president minister said that he did not agree with the project's arguments that the federal executive could not structure the measures to prepare the public administration through general rules.
"I do not think that if it did, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector corresponds to the Federal Executive, who has constitutional mandate, the State's rectory.
Replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years, leading to better use of the radio spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
Deferring change, he said, would be to defer the benefits of digitalization, which implies a decision of public interest, which does not only have a technical dimension, "because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire system established, in accordance with the principle of State economic rectification, includes a group of powers that the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition, and had done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, which somehow invades the sphere of competence of Congress, since compliance with the laws issued by the Legislative is being provided in the administrative sphere, is being assured.
Analysing the possibility of a "vote-by-vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PREP the difference between first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, yet the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total records are not recorded.
The possibility of the count "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Preliminar Electoral Results Programme (PREP) the difference between first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, yet the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total records are not accounted for.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or State Electoral Code or Electoral Justice Act, provided that the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the finalization of the legal period so that they could enter into force in the current electoral process, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided for in the State Official Journal Act, with the argument that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and called the vote of the state president to constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal" as it does not have the right to "punish or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of the "vote by vote", Maria de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In such a way, the partial number of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be given on the assumption that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no scrutiny and computation record in the box file or does not work with the President; or, where there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total number of votes received in all the ballot boxes may be made where there is an indication that the difference between the alleged winner of the election in question and the candidate who obtained the second place in the ballot is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is the express request of the representative of the party and/or coalition who put forward the second of the candidates mentioned.
The total number of votes may also be made if, at the end of the regular count, it is established that the difference between the allegedly winning candidate and the secondly located candidate is equal to or less than a percentage point, provided that there is the express request of the representative of the political party whose candidate has been secondly, in which case the electoral packages that have been partially counted will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation is Morelia's choice, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and the second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total records.
