The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed that country at the edge of the economic disaster
The Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the president of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy at the edge of the economic disaster and has jeopardized the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected that it will present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the result of his discussions with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The framework is now well-delineated," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has driven its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a hard austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the beating confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the yield of the Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were significantly driven by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, who was forced by the crisis to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are meant to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti Government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will probably be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that Monti's failure would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations on Monday.
He'll end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, which has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister will succeed.
Rescueing Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros, would be too much for the current financial defences of the eurozone.
Monti has said that his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before the elections go ahead.
Monti said that he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that it should be made up of only technicians, an indication of their retaliation to a process bound by financial pressure.
Political sources noted that mutual distrust and disagreement between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
