We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we've been growing, it's been easier to find a balance.
We make sure not to be too much of a tour because it's easy to fall into that game of the great crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you that you must respect the music and what brought it, without getting incapable of being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really cares about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was a great thing.
We were a band for almost three years and never published a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were many frustrations because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we're still very close to Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think of the amazing person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was a surprising human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know your work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose it for opening?
Yeah, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked most, so we're looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change Yellow Ledbetter's lyrics live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing he can think of.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
They're so many.
Inside the first ones I can think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
They're so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep the grunge relevant despite being no longer a fashion?
I think all of us always feel a little off-line from the word grunge.
When I think about her, she reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that came up at the same time, and, if there's relevance now, I think it's something wonderful because it's worth listening to music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the result of this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that may seem lighter, but there are also songs, such as The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs although they may sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed touched them, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
