MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Directs Social Security research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents', which will allow for overweight markers.
In a communiqué, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionologists and social workers was integrated.
The team is supported by specialists and graduates from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Research and Advanced Studies Centre (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population to participate whether or not they are entitled to participate, to visit the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 hours.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Sports Unit Cuauhtémoc (State of Poniente Mexico) and that since October 8, the activity was carried out in the Sports Unit Nezahualcóyolt (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is achieved, the study will continue in the Sports Unit (South of the Federal District) and finally in the Sports Unit Morelos (North of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day was held on 14 November, it stated that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and history of the hereditary family of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
It detailed that on Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetics are applied to all participants (genes associated with child obesity are identified).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in weight in minors.
'Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 pointed out that in only six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed', stressed the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others because of their genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translate in the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (heats) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive assessment of children, which allows them to detect whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-coloured folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, indicating the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, doctors give it in writing to parents, who are told each of the measurements and changes in the lifestyle they must make in order to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic sufferings: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, remain most of the day sitting in front of the television and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM Asphalt would Avoid Bachelors
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of the environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the pavement were served, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand baches each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who assured that if the construction and maintenance process of a pavement is the right one, the baches could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
At its conference A technological opinion of the bachelors, issued in the framework of the International Year of Chemicals, announced that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of baches.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, high molecular weights, called asphalts, and other low molecular weights, called Maltese, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, close to 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes broken, he added.
This means that in the streets asphalt resistance is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ investigator noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitutes the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt folder, he abounded, a last layer called rolling folder is placed, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. a sand that also bathes in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the rolling folder also requires to have the proper thickness and care must be taken of the material that is made of.
Climate, especially moisture and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the terrain is wet, the water spreads inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and therefore the formation of baches.
In the process of forming a bachelor, he said, the first to wear is the bearing film and only after it affects the asphalt folder, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be addressed to the first signals with proper maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of baches and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always be related to the vehicle load and ensure that it is fulfilled, in order to avoid the formation of baches frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow for the repair of baches easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
