This was the work of the warmth that identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano.
A Cali lophoscopist passed to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a Cali CTI lophoscopist passed to history as the man who confirmed the identity of the Farc's top chief: "Alfonso Cano", through the match of his digital prints.
Of the seven lophoscopists working in the CTI seccional, that week was the turn of "availability" for Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the start of his career, Gonzalez worked in Chocó municipalities, where he often had to enter the jungle for more than five days to reach the site where the corpses were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after carrying out the corresponding courses, specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against the alias Alfonso Cano to Eliazar warned him to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who directed the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to carry Guillermo León Sáenz's decactilar card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site where the corpse was located, he did not recognize it because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
I was without a beard, dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Along with a galtonian glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body with those of the card.
His eye didn't fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the chief of the Farcs.
In search of the print
For a printer from the Sijín de Cali the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an accurate science, without margin of error, which can become key to crime resolution.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the persons captured.
When captured, many criminals present false papers or have no papers.
We took their fingerprint and searched them in the database.
The investigator said that, in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, for in that place the thief had supported his hand to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to draw a fingerprint, but in that case we could get the fingerprint from the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
Footprints can also rule out or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
They recently found a dead man with bottles of liquor around him.
The investigation determined that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a print in the bottle coincided.
Even though this doesn't guarantee that he was the killer, he places him at the crime scene.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that in objects "the prints are drawn with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplant or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said CTI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown in the CSI TV program.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that touches becomes a print.
However, if it can be used, if the respective match is made.
