In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and take provisions to that end.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Canadian Society, with the participation of six experts from various fields, including ethical, legal and medical.
The Committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code in such a way as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient proposes such an option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
To begin with, experts quote a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks tenth, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death."
With or without medication, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Canadian Royal Society.
And, even though most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying at the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that did not coincide with the Federal Government's position, which had already stated that they did not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or not constituted a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not caused an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or suicide assisted with non-competent persons or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconferencing that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, although it is clearly illegal."
"In Canada assisted suicide is practiced, although it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians, favorable to euthanasia
Let us remember that 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favour of euthanasia, since they believe that it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia does not mean that the lives of older or disabled persons are less valuable.
With regard to persons who have committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent of the respondents believe that a process against them should not be initiated.
With regard to the maintenance or interruption of health care for a patient, the situation is not so clear, as the authors of the report indicate.
Furthermore, among its recommendations it is suggested that the Criminal Code indicate that the withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The Committee of Experts also calls for the training of health professionals in the duty to respect the fact that a patient rejects assistance at the end of his life without fear of facing a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the Committee claims that Governments, health care institutions and doctors work together to ensure the best palliative care, not only in cases of cancer.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canada's health institutions, the Committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, be regarded as euthanasia and be subject to the same procedures.
Other experts express reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations with regard to the findings of the report of experts from the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Descamps, a specialist in Health Law, has described as "extreme" the position of the experts who sign the report, inter alia because the practice of euthanasia is not limited to the patients in the terminal phase.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over 18 years old can ask for help to commit suicide," Deschamps says, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also stressed that the authors of the report seemed to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
However, he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations".
Health Law Specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" with regard to the findings of the report, which she described as a "manifesto in favour of euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, questioned especially the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
