Energy policy:
the facts should be worth more than the dogmas
If there is a topic that cannot be addressed taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect purchasing power and the competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will mean the duplication of electricity demand by 2050, unless a large part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing shortage of fossil resources will need to be alleviated in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, not forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not modify any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to renounce nuclear energy.
This is not the case either of Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor of Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to cite some examples, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to their park, renewing the construction of a power station interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality is against such a speech.
Berlin's choice will lead to an increase in the price of electricity, a greater energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, particularly from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
It must be meditated on the case of Denmark.
Europe's champion in the wind sector, of which 30 per cent of its electricity, is also one of the major coal and gas users due to wind intermittent; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a bill of electricity 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would lead to a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would give rise to the marvelous declarations about the re-industrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of the French refuse to pay and, in fact, they do not express opposition in principle to that type of energy, as the surveys show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost the construction of an industrial sector with 125,000 managerial jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it covers a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and which can create non-localizable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of EUR 6 billion per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would commission an EPR designed to operate for sixty years, when its manufacturer's collapse is scheduled?
In order to solve the equation of nuclear energy, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, nor is there a diabolical source.
The development by Areva of low-carbon and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the maximum level of security.
In France, we have a safety authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not cause any consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobil, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters, which resulted in the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the EPR has a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is studied by all electrical actors who want to build a plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for Areva and EDF competitors, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow the emotion, dogmas and partisana manoeuvres to dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy implemented by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from a variety of points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "the country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped on the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see Libération newspaper of 23 May) proclaiming past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
The question is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the direction stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has nearly two million migrant workers", while on the left, the tone set it Michel Rocard explaining that France "can't take over all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that co-development will help solve the "problem of migration".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restriction of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, in particular the unskilled, by pressuring for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in fact, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly practised in sectors without employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and those most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri estimated that an increase of 1 per cent of migration flows represents a long-term increase in real wages from 0.6 to 0.9 per cent.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity of immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (import less expenditure) of €150,000 to average public budgets throughout his lifetime.
At the beginning of his term of office, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points that he lacked "with his teeth".
Such teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
