The Nord Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the banks of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the opening of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have jointly turned the valve wheel that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western Europe network.
With this new pipeline, a further 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km communicating the San Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 which will allow a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, i.e. sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, we are already talking about the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents victorious atmospheres.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land flows by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
By the way, these two countries lose some power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the top of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet covenant", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to succeed in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that binds us organically," François Fillon confirmed during the opening of the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the large contracts in the gas sector are as political as well as economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom's managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of gas arrival.
The construction of this pipeline also represents a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against the anchors of the ships.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, for caution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream society.
Measures for the protection of fauna and flora were also necessary.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden's waters, but the project managers gave up on it when they saw that the Swedish were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to be established permanently in the sea off their coasts.
"In case of a breakdown, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," Jens Müller says.
In case of leakage, gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that there will be a leak, since they have planned clusters that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a pure, it is introduced into the inner tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full journey days at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any repair.
The circulation of the gas is simply guaranteed by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
To her, the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and exploitation of the gas pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to that company, for a period of twenty-five renewable years, the total capacity for gas transport.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported," Jens Müller says.
The financing of gas pipeline construction has been completed by 30% with shareholders' contributions and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the project should reach €7.4 billion for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenditure.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy shore planted with pine trees.
Valves, with 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas at arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return to people the taste of writing.
It has an air of adventure, from hours of writing to the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as ageed by time.
However, the Moleskine books with the current appearance were born... in 1997.
The Italian fashion company, based on Milan, decided at that time to launch a booklet of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant of the company, was responsible for launching the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (topo skin), which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, inter alia, to cover the banquets.
This type of booklet was highly valued by writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Modo Modo.
And it succeeded.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26 per cent, to a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first few years has remained far away, in which only 3,000 booklets were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, as the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open spirit and cults.
The Italian small company, which had twelve workers in its inception, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in bookstore, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has released the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists expose their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard tapas, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the SG Capital Europe Investment Fund, currently Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the employment of the disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled persons doubled the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
discouraging?
"No," says Eric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress achieved for 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a lot to be done."
It should be mentioned that unemployed persons with disabilities continue to face many obstacles to accessing employment.
They tend to be older: 37% are over 50 years old (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80 per cent have not finished high school and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared with an average of 38 per cent.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the quid of the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; people's mentality progresses, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité said that the respondents have "a level of knowledge about disabilities", with a "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually deficient".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a target set by a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"Now we reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishments "submitted to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, particularly among the large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies owning between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82 per cent of enterprises with between 100 and 199 workers.
